         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0000492">
               <p><persName>Cownley</persName> was spiritually awakened under
                     <persName>JW</persName>&apos;s preaching in <placeName>Bath</placeName> in
                     <date when="1743">1743</date>, and on returning to his native
                     <placeName>Leominster</placeName> joined the Methodist society there and began
                  to preach. By the <date when="1746">1746</date> Conference he was an Assistant,
                  and <persName>JW</persName> described him as &apos;one of the best preachers in
                     <placeName>England</placeName>&apos;. He traveled widely as an <seg
                     ana="itinerancy">itinerant preacher</seg>, notably in
                     <placeName>Ireland</placeName> and the north of <placeName>England</placeName>.
                  In <date when="1755-10">Oct. 1755</date> he married <persName>Martha Susannah
                     (&apos;Suky&apos;) Massiot</persName> of <placeName>Cork</placeName>. See
                  Atmore, <hi rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 90–94; <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>,
                  261–62; <hi rend="italic">EMP</hi>, 2:1–47; <hi rend="italic">Minutes</hi>
                  (post-Wesley, <date when="1793">1793</date>), 2:275; and Vickers, <hi
                     rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 82.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
